                <head>26. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>On December 5, 1963, President <persName corresp="#p_JLB1">Lyndon B.
                        Johnson</persName> chaired the first National Security Council meeting of
                    his administration. Because there was no Vice President, the President invited
                    Representative Sam Rayburn of Texas to attend National Security Council meetings
                    “from time to time as his schedule permitted.” Rayburn was
                        <persName>Johnson</persName>’s successor in the event of the President’s
                    death in office. For an outline of remarks <persName corresp="#p_BMG2"
                        >Bundy</persName> prepared for the President and the summary record of this
                    520th <gloss target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> meeting, see <ref
                        target="frus1961-63v08#d149">
                        <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1961–1963, volume VIII, Documents
                        149</ref> and <ref target="frus1961-63v08#d150">150</ref>. See also
                        <persName corresp="#p_SBK1">Smith</persName>, <hi rend="italic"
                        >Organizational History of the National Security Council</hi>, page 57.</p>
            </div>
